  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite its publication in 2021, \"The Global Horizon\" has yet to establish a measurable academic and public impact, with no recorded citations or community discourse. However, the book demonstrates potential for commercial interest as indicated by its presence on platforms like Amazon and Goodreads.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published by Leuven University Press in 2021, \"The Global Horizon\" currently stands without any recorded citations or community discussions across various online platforms, including Wikipedia, Reddit, or Bluesky. This lack of engagement suggests that, while the work may provide valuable insights, it has not yet gained significant traction within the scholarly community or popular discourse.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite the absence of overt academic metrics, the book demonstrates a degree of commercial interest, evidenced by its availability on prominent retail websites such as Amazon and Goodreads. This suggests that there may be a market or audience that could derive value from the content, although it has not translated into scholarly uptake yet.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The data indicates a potential for scholarly relevance in the future, as it is mentioned that there is some association with sustainability and policy relevance, linked to the Sustainable Development Goals. This connection may resonate with specific academic discussions or initiatives, highlighting an area of potential scholarly engagement moving forward.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In conclusion, \"The Global Horizon\" is positioned within an academic framework that suggests it has yet to be fully explored or cited within the literature. It may serve as a resource in commercial spaces while holding untapped potential for engagement in both scholarly and public discussions, which could evolve with time and new developments in the field.</p>",
